{"id":"2211.07176","submitter":"Rahul Deshpande","authors":"Rahul Deshpande, Dileep Chandran, Alexander J. Smits, Ivan Marusic","title":"On the relationship between manipulated inter-scale phase and\n  energy-efficient turbulent drag reduction","comments":"Preprint submitted to the Journal of Fluid Mechanics after first\n  revision, with 14 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the role of inter-scale interactions in the high-Reynolds\nnumber skin-friction drag reduction strategy reported by Marusic et al. (Nat.\nCommun., vol. 12, 2021). The strategy involves imposing relatively\nlow-frequency streamwise travelling waves of spanwise velocity at the wall to\nactuate the drag generating outer-scales. This approach has proven to be more\nenergy-efficient than the conventional method of directly targeting the drag\nproducing inner-scales, which typically requires actuation at higher\nfrequencies. Notably, it is observed that actuating the outer-scales at low\nfrequencies leads to a substantial attenuation of the major drag producing\ninner-scales. In the present study, we find that increased drag reduction, on\nimposition of spanwise wall oscillations, is always associated with an\nincreased coupling between the inner and outer scales. This enhanced coupling\nemerges through manipulation of the phase relationships between these\ntriadically linked scales, with the actuation forcing the entire range of\nenergy-containing scales, from the inner (viscous) to the outer (inertial)\nscales, to be more in-phase. The energy-efficient drag reduction strategy is\nexpected to further improve at very high Reynolds numbers, where the energised\nouter-scales are known to more strongly superimpose and modulate the\ninner-scales. This Reynolds number dependence of the non-linear coupling is\nalso shown to be a consequence of the manipulated inter-scale phase\nrelationships, by analyzing canonical boundary layer data across a large\nReynolds number range. Leveraging inter-scale interactions, therefore, offers a\nplausible mechanism for achieving energy-efficient drag reduction at high\nReynolds numbers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 14 Nov 2022 08:12:32 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 8 May 2023 08:19:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-09"}
